| Feature                     | MQTT                                                                                   | HTTP                                                           |
| --------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Architecture Pattern**    | Publish/Subscribe using a broker                                                       | Client–Server Request/Response                                 |
| **Data Transfer Model**     | Asynchronous messaging                                                                 | Synchronous request and response                               |
| **Power Consumption**       | Low (suitable for battery-powered devices)                                             | Higher due to repeated connections and larger headers          |
| **Latency**                 | Very low                                                                               | Higher than MQTT                                               |
| **IoT Suitability**         | Excellent for real-time IoT applications                                               | Better for web applications and REST APIs                      |
| **Bandwidth Usage**         | Low bandwidth with small packet size                                                   | Higher bandwidth due to HTTP headers                           |
| **Reliability**             | Supports QoS 0, 1, and 2 for reliable delivery                                         | Relies on TCP; no built-in QoS levels for application messages |
| **Security Considerations** | TLS/SSL encryption, username/password authentication, certificate-based authentication | HTTPS (TLS/SSL), OAuth, API keys, token-based authentication   |
Reasons:

It consumes much less bandwidth than HTTP.
It has lower power consumption, extending battery life for field sensors.
The publish/subscribe model allows one broker to efficiently communicate with thousands of sensor nodes.
Built-in QoS levels ensure reliable message delivery even with unstable network connections.
MQTT supports near real-time communication, making it suitable for monitoring soil moisture, temperature, humidity, and irrigation status.
MQTT can operate efficiently over low-bandwidth or unreliable wireless networks common in rural areas.

Conclusion:
MQTT is the better choice for a 1000-node smart agriculture deployment because it is lightweight, scalable, energy-efficient, and specifically designed for IoT communication.
HTTP is more appropriate for web services and REST APIs, but it is less efficient for large-scale IoT sensor networks.
